# LAMMPS Input File  (figure: two-phase coexistence, grown solid)
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package
# Modernized recreation of the MSU/CAVS tutorials by Mark A. Tschopp
# Tutorial 15, part 2 (step 1 of 2): build a solid-liquid two-phase cell of
# fcc aluminum.  A pre-existing interface removes the nucleation barrier that
# made the one-phase estimate of part 1 so uncertain.  The companion script
# velocity.lmp then reads the cell back and measures the melting point from
# the direction the interface moves.
#
# This uses the Mendelev et al. aluminum potential, which is fitted for
# liquid structure and solid-liquid coexistence and reproduces the melting
# point well.

units metal
atom_style atomic
boundary p p p
lattice fcc 4.05
region box block 0 5 0 5 0 20            # square cross-section, elongated along z
create_box 1 box
create_atoms 1 box
mass 1 26.98
pair_style eam/fs
pair_coeff * * ../Al_mm.eam.fs Al
velocity all create 800.0 7654 mom yes rot yes
timestep 0.002
thermo 5000

# 1) equilibrate the whole crystal well BELOW the melting point so it stays
#    solid.  The barostat keeps the square cross-section that the cubic
#    crystal wants (x and y coupled, so they relax together) while the long
#    z axis relaxes on its own:
fix eq all npt temp 800.0 800.0 0.2 x 0.0 0.0 2.0 y 0.0 0.0 2.0 z 0.0 0.0 2.0 couple xy
run 10000
unfix eq

# 2) split the cell into a lower half (kept solid) and an upper half (to be
#    melted) and create the interface: drive the upper half hot with a local
#    Langevin thermostat while a second one holds the lower half cold and
#    crystalline.  Now barostat ONLY z, so the less-dense liquid can expand
#    along the interface normal without straining the solid cross-section
#    (an x-y barostat here would let the liquid pull the lattice apart):
variable zmid equal zlo+(zhi-zlo)/2.0
region rtop block INF INF INF INF ${zmid} INF units box
group top region rtop
group bot subtract all top
fix baro all nph z 0.0 0.0 2.0
fix hot  top langevin 1400.0 1400.0 0.1 11111   # melt the upper half
fix cold bot langevin  800.0  800.0 0.1 22222   # keep the lower half solid
run 12000
unfix hot
unfix cold

# 3) directional growth: the upper half is now a supercooled liquid (below Tm)
#    and freezes onto the cold solid interface -- the front advances upward

unfix baro
fix baro all nph x 0 0 2 y 0 0 2 z 0 0 2 couple xy
fix th all langevin 890 890 0.1 4321
run 15000
unfix th
unfix baro

# 4) inherent structure: minimize so CNA cleanly separates solid from liquid
minimize 1.0e-6 1.0e-6 2000 20000
compute cna all cna/atom 3.5
variable isfcc atom "c_cna==1"
compute nfcc all reduce sum v_isfcc
thermo_style custom step pe c_nfcc
run 0
print "fcc-coordinated atoms after minimization: $(c_nfcc) of 2000"

# pale-red plane at the (current) box center marks the original interface

region divide block INF INF INF INF $(zlo+(zhi-zlo)/2.0-0.01) $(zlo+(zhi-zlo)/2.0+0.01) units box

write_dump all image coexist-grown.png c_cna type adiam 3.0 &
    view 80 15 up 0 1 0 zoom 4.0 size 800 800 shiny 0.15 fsaa yes ssao yes 7123 0.6 &
    box yes 0.02 &
    region divide lightcoral frame 0.5 &
    modify backcolor white boxcolor midnightblue &
    amap 1 5 sa 1.0 5 steelblue purple green red gray &
    lights 0.2 0.9 0.5 0.9
